reating a new one. A dedicated class in its own file seems good. However, I see potential issues with not being able to directly test getDeclaredConstructors in DiscoverySuite if a class is already runnable, especially regarding wrapper class constructor effects. Moreover, Discovery's accessibleSuites might miss `DiscoveryRunnerWrappedClass` due to how processClassName and annotations work. There could also be concerns about suite order and property settings before assertions.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Assessing discovery issues**\\n\\nI'm encountering a potential issue where discovery scans all class files, including nested support classes, which might leave out `DiscoveryRunnerWrappedClassSuite` due to its lack of a no-arg constructor. I could define a support package under `org_scalatest.scalatest_core_2_13.discovery`, but I need to be cautious with wildcard strings. I should mention that we didn't run tests as per instructions—though, I'm not sure if the user expected that. Also, the untracked metadata directory should remain untouched. I think I might say, \\\"Note: existing untracked metadata directory was present and untouched\\\" for clarity.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Reviewing package issues**\\n\\nI'm double-checking to ensure that no source package matches the library, specifically verifying that `org_scalatest` isn't the same as `org.scalatest`. I see a possible issue: the companion object for `DiscoverySuiteTest` is in the test package and at the top level. This makes me wonder if test class discovery could mistakenly identify `DiscoverySuiteTest`, but since it doesn't extend Suite, that's probably not relevant. I'm also considering potential grammar issues with the Scala code, particularly if the package block appears after the object.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Implemented a dedicated Scala test for the active dynamic-access class:\n\n- Added `tests/src/org.scalatest/scalatest-core_2.13/3.2.19/src/test/scala/or